                <h2>Instagram setup</h2>
                <h4><strong>Access token</strong></h4>
                <p>Follow the link in the module, under the <em>"Instagram setup"</em> tab, grant our app access &mdash; you might be prompted to log in &mdash; and an Access Token will be generated for you.</p>
                <p>Simply paste that into the field in the module configuration page. <em>Make sure you copy the entire token and don't have an extra space before or after it.</em></p>
                <p>Hit <em>"Save all"</em> and your done!</p>
                <hr>
                <h2>Feed settings</h2>
                <p>This entire section is for the following hook positions: Home, footer, left and right column.</p>
                <h4><strong>Number of photos</strong></h4>
                <p>This decides how many photos to fetch from Instagram. The Instagram API has a limit of 20 photos per request so even if you put a higher number than 20, 20 is the number that will be used.</p>
                <h4><strong>Feed style</strong></h4>
                <p>The style of the feed. Square, rounded (5px border radius), or circle (completely round).</p>
                <h4><strong>Spacing</strong></h4>
                <p>This controls the spacing between each photo in your feed.</p>
                <h4><strong>Carousel</strong></h4>
                <p>Whether or not to use and activate the carousel functionality.</p>
                <h4><strong>Infite loop</strong></h4>
                <p>If the carousel should continue to loop around when the user reaches the end, instead of just stopping.</p>
                <h4><strong>Breakpoints</strong></h4>
                <p>These breakpoints work from small to large. This way you can decide how many photos (or carousel items) you wish to display depending on the current breakpoint.</p>
                <p><em>Extra small</em> - From 0px upwards</p>
                <p><em>Small</em> - From 480px upwards</p>
                <p><em>Medium</em> - From 768px upwards</p>
                <p><em>Large</em> - From 992px upwards</p>
                <p><em>Extra large</em> - From 1180px upwards</p>
                <h4><strong>Number of columns</strong></h4>
                <p>If you're not using the carousel, this will more or less be the same as the breakpoint settings above. The number of columns in different breakpoints, working from small to large.</p>
                <p><em>Extra small</em> - From 0px upwards</p>
                <p><em>Small</em> - From 480px upwards</p>
                <p><em>Medium</em> - From 768px upwards</p>
                <p><em>Large</em> - From 992px upwards</p>
                <p><em>Extra large</em> - From 1180px upwards</p>
                <h4><strong>Hover background color</strong></h4>
                <p>What background color to use when you hover over the photo. You can use hex and rgba.</p>
                <h4><strong>Hover text color</strong></h4>
                <p>What text color to use when you hover over the photo. You can use hex and rgba.</p>
                <h3>Show likes</h3>
                <p>Whether or not to display how many likes each photo have got on hover.</p>
                <h3>Show comments</h3>
                <p>Whether or not to display how many comments each photo have got on hover.</p>
                <h4><strong>Modal functionality</strong></h4>
                <p>By default, the photo is linked to it's page on the Instagram site. With the modal functionality you can open it up, in a modal, and you will then see the embedded version of that photo.</p>
                <h4><strong>Hook position</strong></h4>
                <p>Where you want this particular feed hooked.</p>
                <hr>
